Question: Java Sockets: Send multiple lines and receive multiple lines [duplicate]:
I am sending multiple lines to a ServerSocket using a PrintWriter.
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.write("1");
printWriter.write("2");
printWriter.write("3");
Then I am trying to receive it with a BufferedReader
ServerSocket serverSocket = ...
Socket socket = serverSocket.accept();
BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream()));
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine());
I am of course closing all the resources, I wrote this code only to visualize the problem. That prints 123 but it is supposed to print 1. How can I fix that?

Please using this api: BufferedReader.readLine.
Answer:<<<api>>>: BufferedReader.readLine
<<<code>>>: try { System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine()); } catch (Exception e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
<<<explanation>>>: The BufferedReader.readLine() method reads a line of text. It returns the next line of text from the input stream. The line is terminated by any one of a line separator, a carriage return, a carriage return followed immediately by a newline, or a newline.

In your case, you are sending "1", "2", and "3" as separate lines. When you call bufferedReader.readLine(), it reads the first line "1" and then returns it. The remaining lines "2" and "3" are still in the input buffer of the BufferedReader, but they are not read because the readLine() method has already returned "1".

To fix this, you should call readLine() in a loop until there are no more lines to read. Here is an example:

```java
String line;
while ((line = bufferedReader.readLine()) != null) {
    System.out.println(line);
}
```

This will read all lines from the input stream and print them.
